x4freetext: Harwell Variable Energy Cyclotron
.The recoil range distributions were measured
by irradiating a thin iron target backed by a stack of
thin aluminium catcher foils.
.Digitizing error of data.

20.02.2008, repeat letter 11.07.2008.No reply.
SB
fig.1
The stack comprised 24 foils each of nominal thickness
12.5 mum, the actual thickness of each foil being
determined by weighing. The stack of foil was mounted
inside an electrically-suppressed Faraday cup.
a 13.5% efficient Ge(Li) detector
*By author*.The activity of each product detected was
obtained brom the measured count rates using the known
detector efficiency and published gamma-ray branching
ratios.
The uncertainy in the final cross-section is dominated
by the uncertainty in determinating the foil
thicknesses and is estimated as 10%.
Finaly, the beam energy on exit from each foil was
determined from the foil thicknesses.

x4freetext: Fig.2
The target used had a nominal thickness of 2.5 mum and
was mounted normal to the beam except during the
measurement of spectra close to 90 degree when the
target angle was displaced by 15 degree.
Particle identification was achieved
using a delta-E-E telescope of two silicon detectors-
a 15 mum delta-E detector was used for most of the
measurements.
A 100 mum delta-E detector was used to measure the
deuteron spectra at forward angles and the proton
spectra above 8 MeV, a 3000 mum E-detector being using
throughout.
The absolute normalization of the spectra may be
systematically uncertain by up to 15%. This is due to
uncertainties in detector solid angles and the target
thickness.
